{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17626472","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17626472"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:38:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:38:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17077"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17077"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.05,0.08,0.08,0.7]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9767"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77509"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9767","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9767"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17077"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63021"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"},{"type":"tags","id":"5262"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22945"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23171"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77509"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFluoroquinolone antibiotics are broad-spectrum antimicrobial agents commonly used to treat various bacterial infections, including urinary tract infections, pneumonia, and gastrointestinal infections. They are particularly effective against gram-negative organisms such as \u003Cem\u003EEscherichia coli\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of fluoroquinolone antibiotics?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inhibits peptidoglycan cross-linking in cell walls","Prevents formation of bacterial tetrahydrofolate","Disrupts phospholipid structure in cell membranes","Blocks bacterial ribosomal protein assembly","Binds to DNA-enzyme complexes to inhibit DNA synthesis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFluoroquinolones work by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to DNA-enzyme complexes to inhibit DNA synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E. These antibiotics are bactericidal. Fluoroquinolones target complexes between DNA and  two enzymes, DNA gyrase and topoisomerase IV. The accumulation of these complexes disrupts the replication fork and causes breakage and cleavage of the DNA strand, leading to cell death. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen these enzymes are inhibited, DNA replication cannot proceed, leading to bacterial cell death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits peptidoglycan cross-linking in cell walls\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of beta-lactam antibiotics like penicillins and cephalosporins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevents formation of bacterial tetrahydrofolate\u003C/strong\u003E is how sulfonamides and trimethoprim work\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisrupts phospholipid structure in cell membranes\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of polymyxins and daptomycin\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks bacterial ribosomal protein assembly\u003C/strong\u003E is how aminoglycosides and tetracyclines work\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fluoroquinolone antibiotics work by inhibiting complexes of DNA and DNA gyrase and topoisomerase IV, to prevent DNA replication and cause cell death","DNA gyrase is the primary target in gram-negative bacteria while topoisomerase IV is the primary target in gram-positive bacteria.","Fluoroquinolones are particularly effective against urinary tract infections, respiratory tract infections, and gastrointestinal infections."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63021"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17077"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63021","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63021"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T10:36:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T10:36:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9767"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77509"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","i